### Conclusion

A unified API compatibility checker is profoundly powerful, provided you do not try to unify the *parsing mechanics*. By grounding your abstract model in **I/O Contravariance and Covariance**, treating defaults as **structural bridges but semantic risks**, and allowing static schema math to be overridden by **empirical telemetry**, you create a tool that respects the rigid physics of binary serialization while accommodating the fluid, usage-driven reality of modern APIs.